International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Fri, 28 May 2004 09:11:07 -0300
From: Carlos Brisola Marcondes <cbrisola@mbox1.ufsc.br>
Source: Folha de SÃ£o Paulo 28 May 2004 [in Portuguese, trans. by
Mods.JW/MPP] [edited]
<http://www1.folha.uol.com.br/folha/cotidiano/ult95u94885.shtml>

The Secretary of Health of the Federal District [Brasilia] confirmed on
Thursday 4 deaths occurring since early Sunday morning [late Saturday
night] caused by an as-yet-unidentified illness.
The latest death was in a 24-year-old male who whas admitted [to the
hospital] with difficulties breathing. 3 of the 4 deaths were residents of
the satellite city of Sao Sebastiao [population 70 000 mixed urban/rural
community - Mod.JW], and one was from Paranoa.
In all of the cases, the presentation was similar: headache, fever, muscle
pains, diarrhea, and difficulty breathing. Another 3 persons presented
with the same symptoms and have been hospitalized for observation. Of
these 3, 2 are improving, and one is in intensive care.
There is widespread concern in the area, with many persons without symptoms
reporting to the hospitals to be checked. To release the pressure on the
public health units, [health] posts are being set up in the public schools
of Sao Sebastiao. The teams are identifying suspected cases and referring
them to the hospitals in the city.
Health workers are investigating the etiology of the illness, including
interviews, collection of information on habits of the deceased, and
collection of specimens of water, mosquitoes, and rats for analysis. The
investigators have not discarded the diagnoses of hepatitis and dengue
hemorraghic fever [in contrast with the earlier news report, which
mentioned these diagnoses had been excluded - Mod.MPP]. Hantavirus and
leptospirosis are under investigation as well.
--
Carlos Brisola Marcondes
<cbrisola@mbox1.ufsc.br>
[Additional information from an earlier version of this same article
mentioned that the 4th case was a 24-year-old male who had been ill for 4
days before arriving at the Base Hospital, Brasilia, in serious condition,
on Wed 26 May 2004. There was also mention that 15 individuals had been
placed under observation of whom 3 were hospitalized. - Mods.MPP/JW]
