[2]
Date: Fri, 28 May 2004 08:32:07 EDT
From: Raymond Weinstein, MD <AlaskaRay@aol.com>

I would be interested in learning whether blood cultures or any gram stains
were performed. The prodromal symptoms described (fever, headache, and
weakness) followed fairly quickly by death, is the norm in most cases of
systemic anthrax. In addition, hemorrhagic pleural effusions and pulmonary
edema are usually found at autopsy, even if the case is not considered to
be inhalational anthrax. Other common symptoms of anthrax include upper
abdominal pain, chest pain, cough and dyspnea. Other frequent autopsy
findings in anthrax include hemorrhagic mediastinitis and hemorrhagic
meningitis, often with subarachnoid hemorrhage.
--
Raymond Weinstein, MD
National Center for Biodefense
George Mason University
Manassas, Va.
<AlaskaRay@aol.com>
[The etiology of this apparent cluster remains unknown. Today's newswire
provides the additional symptoms of diarrhea and muscle pains. Of
interest, using the Global Infectious Disease and Epidemiology Network
(GIDEON <http://www.gideononline.com>) software, the 2 leading diagnoses
for consideration with the above symptom complex (fever, headache, muscle
pain, diarrhea and respiratory distress) are leptospirosis and
hantavirus. Of curiosity is that the Brasilia area is at the tail end of
the dry season; hence, the risk of widespread exposure to leptospirosis
would be reduced, unless there were unseasonal heavy rains in the preceding
period that would have led to flooding and general exposure to water
contaminated with rat droppings. Again, more information on this apparent
cluster from knowledgeable sources would be appreciated. - Mod.MPP]
